The `setState` method in React is used to update the state of a component. It is used to change the value of a component's state variable, which in turn, triggers a re-rendering of the component. This allows the component to update its UI based on the new state value.

The `setState` function takes two arguments: the current state object and a new state object. The new state object can be an object with new values or a function that returns a new state object.

Here is an example of updating an array's properties using `setState`:

```javascript
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
  constructor() {
    super();
    this.state = {
      items: [
        { name: 'Item 1', price: 10 },
        { name: "Item 2", price: 20 },
      ],
    };
  }

  handleAddItem = () => {
    this.setState(prevState => ({
      items: [...prevState.items, { name: "New Item", price: 30 }],
    }));
  };

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <button onClick={this.handleAddItem}>Add Item</button>
        <ul>
          {this.state.items.map(item => (
            <li key={item.name}>{item.name} - {item.price}</li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

In this example, we have a `MyComponent` that has a state variable `items` that holds an array of objects. When the user clicks the "Add Item" button, the `handleAddItem` function is called, which updates the state variable `items` by adding a new item to the end of the array. This causes the component to re-render and display the new array of items.

